WEBVTT

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:10.860
Good afternoon.

00:00:10.910 --> 00:00:13.100
Welcome to the open source
Apple and You session.

00:00:13.100 --> 00:00:17.190
We're going to spend a few
minutes today and talk a bit about

00:00:17.270 --> 00:00:20.510
Apple's open source projects,
what we're doing with our open

00:00:20.510 --> 00:00:23.920
source efforts here at Apple,
where we're going to be going from here,

00:00:23.930 --> 00:00:27.860
and probably the most important aspect
of it is how you guys can participate.

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:33.320
If you've been following
us over the past few years,

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:36.760
you've noticed we have a
number of open source projects.

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:43.190
We'll give you some status on
these and some new stuff as well.

00:00:45.460 --> 00:00:48.040
To kind of get into that,
we have a few new open source

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.200
projects we'd like to announce today.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:52.460
The first one is Open Directory.

00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:56.590
This one now joins the rest
of the open source projects.

00:00:56.600 --> 00:01:02.940
Open Directory is our, basically,
directory services layer of Mac OS X.

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:07.370
The abstraction layer of the system
for dealing with directory service,

00:01:07.470 --> 00:01:10.810
the interfaces into things like
LDAP and NetInfo and a number of

00:01:10.810 --> 00:01:13.100
other directory service solutions.

00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:17.090
The next one is CUPS,
which is our new common

00:01:17.090 --> 00:01:21.180
Unix printing system,
which is kind of the

00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:25.270
underlying technology for the
new print system in Jaguar.

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.750
and a bunch of additional Darwin goodies.

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:32.560
Things like IPv6,
which is now part of Jaguar, IPsec,

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:37.920
and we've also integrated OpenLDAP,
NetSNMP, and PAM for some of the

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:40.050
security services and such.

00:01:40.070 --> 00:01:43.400
And there's a number of other
projects that have been updated and

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:46.930
other bits and pieces of Darwin that
are all brand spanking new.

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:50.100
And in addition,
we've added yet more pieces

00:01:50.170 --> 00:01:52.010
from Core Foundation.

00:01:52.340 --> 00:01:55.750
You know, I've been kind of slowly
but surely in CF Lite,

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.150
that's part of Darwin,
and adding more pieces from the

00:01:59.230 --> 00:02:02.060
Core Foundation and bringing that
down into the open source layer.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:06.660
It kind of represents the kind of
the insulation layer between the

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:10.920
Darwin open source activities and
the rest of the Mac OS X world.

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:14.420
And so as those,
since that line is fairly blurry,

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:16.710
we have been trying to bring
technologies that make sense

00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:18.180
down into the open source layer.

00:02:23.090 --> 00:02:26.570
Common Data Security Architecture,
or CDSA, is one we actually

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:28.040
open sourced last year.

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:31.780
But it's one of particular interest,
and I would hope if you haven't

00:02:31.870 --> 00:02:34.290
had a chance to get involved in it,
you would.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:39.410
CDSA is actually an open group standard,
and it's basically the layer

00:02:39.410 --> 00:02:44.640
that deals with security,
number of security features in Mac OS X,

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:48.140
specifically things like encryption
and authentication in particular.

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:52.430
As I mentioned earlier, just briefly,
we now have PAM support

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:54.140
as part of Darwin.

00:02:54.140 --> 00:02:57.280
Basically, PAM is programmable
authentication modules,

00:02:57.280 --> 00:03:02.600
which allow a common way to deal with
authentication at the command line.

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:05.600
The various tools, things like Telnet,
stuff like that,

00:03:05.630 --> 00:03:09.380
that may need authentication,
go through one common set

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:11.680
of libraries called PAM.

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:15.240
Well,
PAM is actually integrated into CDSA,

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:20.150
our security framework for Mac OS X,
so that there is one consistent set

00:03:20.150 --> 00:03:23.660
of behaviors for how authentication
is done within the system.

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:29.380
CDSA also provides a number of plug-in
mechanisms for being able to deal with,

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:33.010
again, cryptography,
for certificate management stuff,

00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:36.720
and for key management and
other authentication pieces.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:41.990
I think the most important message we'd
like to get out around CDSA is that,

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:48.280
one, it's an incredibly powerful set of
abstractions for dealing with security,

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:52.600
and if you are working with code,
for example, that uses OpenSSL,

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:56.900
CDSA is actually something that
we believe should be replacing

00:03:56.900 --> 00:04:01.080
OpenSSL as a way for doing secure
transport kinds of services.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:05.920
And the reason being is that CDSA allows
so many more ways to be able to

00:04:05.990 --> 00:04:09.920
support authentication and encryption,
whereas OpenSSL does a great

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:14.180
job of handling the secure
sockets layer communication,

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:18.300
but doesn't provide very many ways for
dealing with different types of security.

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:20.760
Certificates are things like
smart cards or other types

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:22.270
of authentication services.

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:24.270
Thank you.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:29.960
Other technology we've rolled into
Darwin includes IPv6 and IPSec.

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:33.390
This is actually some
pretty exciting work,

00:04:33.390 --> 00:04:38.170
and we've been working with a COM-A team
to actually get this into Darwin.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:44.380
We're excited to announce that the
COM-A team will be joined as committers

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.080
as part of the Darwin open source effort.

00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:52.270
The documentation project is another
important one which I encourage

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:53.900
people to get involved with.

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:56.700
We never have enough documentation
for all the technology we have.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.900
There are some key pieces that
we support as part of our open

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.900
source efforts so you can help out.

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:06.060
A HeaderDoc, which is a set of tools for
being able to have embedded

00:05:06.060 --> 00:05:09.790
documentation within source code,
within the headers.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:15.570
I/O Kit uses this heavily so that
basically all the APIs and services

00:05:15.570 --> 00:05:18.780
for I/O Kit are actually embedded
in the headers for the source code.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:21.740
And HeaderDoc extracts all
that and presents it in an

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:23.920
HTML format so it's web-browsable.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:28.810
There's a number of ways that you
can get involved in documentation

00:05:28.810 --> 00:05:33.240
efforts in the open source,
particularly in how-tos,

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:37.140
helping with things like man pages
and XML tools and other things.

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:39.480
There's quite a lot of things
that you can get involved with.

00:05:39.790 --> 00:05:44.360
We've done a lot in Jaguar to bring a
number of man pages onto the system,

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:45.720
but there's a lot more yet to be done.

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:47.720
So, you know, come land to hand.

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:52.950
We've, as far as more specific and
focused documentation within

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:56.770
our documentation efforts,
I/O Kit and other kind of bits

00:05:56.770 --> 00:06:01.100
and pieces of the I/O system have
been documented at various levels.

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:04.000
There's another of online full
documents for these things,

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:06.440
as well as a number of
kernel pieces and such.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.850
So if you haven't had a
chance to go check out the

00:06:08.870 --> 00:06:11.220
site and see what we've got,
we've got to encourage you to do so.

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:17.040
So the key thing with open source
is it's not just an Apple effort,

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:17.940
it's a community effort.

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:23.140
And we've been working really hard to
create opportunities for collaboration.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:26.590
And there's actually a lot of folks
who have been working really hard

00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:30.780
with us and on their own to help
contribute to our open source efforts.

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:37.670
In particular, just in the Darwin layer,
we've been working directly

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:38.720
with the FreeBSD team.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:40.710
There's the work on PAM.

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:43.200
A lot of the work of integrating
that actually came from one

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:44.720
of our open source developers.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:46.650
Of course, Patchy is a key partner.

00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:48.720
And then a number of other services.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:54.700
X386 is another key one who has
been also working very hard.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.720
A lot of folks in the community
doing some great work.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:07:04.060
The Darwin community has actually been
remarkably busy in taking Darwin and

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:06.720
moving it onto the x86 platform.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:08.340
And in fact, just recently, I believe,
we had a meeting with a group

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:08.340
of people at the Darwin Center.

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:10.340
They've got it up and running
now on AMD chips as well.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:16.530
So if you're interested in playing
it open source at the core level,

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:20.320
all the Core OS pieces have actually
been ported to another platform.

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:24.340
The streaming server has also been
ported to a number of platforms.

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:26.340
It runs on Linux and Windows.

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:30.340
And we'll tell you a bit more about
that later in the session here.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:32.260
But it's pretty exciting.

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:34.110
It's all over the place.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.100
And the same for open play.

00:07:36.390 --> 00:07:37.830
It's great to see not only the
technologies that run on our platform,

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:37.840
but also the capabilities that we have.

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:42.910
But to really take advantage of the
open source movement is to really get

00:07:42.910 --> 00:07:45.700
them into even broader communities.

00:07:45.950 --> 00:07:49.360
I think one of the most exciting things
that was just announced last night,

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:52.460
if you guys saw the press release,
is that the OpenOffice project

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:55.160
is being ported to Mac OS X.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:57.570
And we'll give you a little bit more
information about that in a little bit.

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:59.380
But it's pretty exciting.

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:01.960
It's quite an impressive
piece of software.

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:06.350
And then I think probably the most
important thing from our open source

00:08:06.420 --> 00:08:10.950
efforts is the fact that last week
we helped launch OpenDarwin.org,

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:14.170
which is basically a way for
more people to get involved

00:08:14.170 --> 00:08:16.220
in the open source activities.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:20.540
Darwin, our opensource.apple.com efforts
have been great for kind of

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:24.130
publishing the open source,
and we have some great relationships

00:08:24.130 --> 00:08:25.700
with a number of committers.

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:28.400
But to really make it work,
we need to allow it really

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:31.780
to be opened up even further,
to allow more forms of communication

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:34.050
and ways that people can participate in.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:38.790
And OpenDarwin.org really allows
the community to help drive the

00:08:38.790 --> 00:08:41.040
open source efforts in key ways.

00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:43.210
and we'll talk more about
that in a few minutes as well.

00:08:44.970 --> 00:08:46.920
So a number of new Darwin committers.

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:51.360
Darwin committers are folks that we've
established an even tighter relationship

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:56.920
and they have right access to our open
source repositories and can make changes.

00:08:56.920 --> 00:09:01.650
And there's folks from the CAMA team,
a number of documentation folks

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:06.380
who have joined the committee list,
and Robert Watson who's actually

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.480
dealing with the trusted BSD.

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:12.350
There's a whole effort on
creating a secure trusted

00:09:12.350 --> 00:09:14.730
OS platform based on Darwin.

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:16.000
- Mm-mm.

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:18.480
So we have a number of folks who
are going to come and tell you more

00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:20.500
about the various technologies.

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:22.450
And next up on the
list is Jordan Hubbard,

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:24.100
who will tell you about Darwin.

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:41.390
I manage the BSD technology
group at Apple,

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:44.030
and we're basically the folks
who are tasked with merging all

00:09:44.030 --> 00:09:45.420
the good bits from free BSD.

00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:50.090
We also do the official
Darwin releases for PowerPC and x86.

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:55.620
I'm going to talk a little bit
about the evolution of Darwin,

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:59.520
and what we've done with the
Open Darwin project recently,

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:00.630
if this would work.

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:04.020
Okay, oh yes, point it the right way.

00:10:04.030 --> 00:10:08.700
So, in the three years
since we started Darwin,

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:12.190
we've gotten a lot of feedback
on how the project is run,

00:10:12.190 --> 00:10:13.540
both good and bad.

00:10:13.540 --> 00:10:17.030
People obviously really like the
idea of Apple doing open source

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:20.470
and participating to this extent,
but they've wanted more

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:24.520
consistent and real-time access
to bug tracking information.

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:28.050
They've wanted to have more people
be able to change the sources.

00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:32.360
One thing about the way Darwin is run,
which is kind of cool actually,

00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:36.270
is that you have access to
the live CVS repository.

00:10:36.310 --> 00:10:39.010
So, if you make a change,
it's a Darwin committer that goes

00:10:39.030 --> 00:10:42.130
straight into the active sources
that we use to build a product.

00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:45.990
The downside of that is that you
have access to the live repository,

00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:49.260
and as you might expect,
there are considerable controls

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:53.090
that are put on this process in
order that people not break stuff.

00:10:53.160 --> 00:10:57.920
So, there needed to be... sort
of a wider access without

00:10:57.940 --> 00:11:00.190
a complete loss of control,
and I'll talk a little

00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:01.050
bit more about that.

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:03.950
Another thing that people
have been asking for is

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:05.800
more access to project news.

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:09.340
They want to be able to put up
bulletins when some significant event

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:11.720
in the open source space takes place.

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:14.470
They want to evangelize and
announce their own little

00:11:14.590 --> 00:11:16.140
sub-projects or working groups.

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:19.000
And while marketing has been sort
of the sole arbiter of what goes

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.220
up on the open source website,
this is pretty slow to change

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:24.300
and pretty tightly controlled.

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:29.430
Um... And they just... Basically,
the community has wanted to

00:11:29.430 --> 00:11:32.060
drive the presentation of
Darwin to a much greater extent.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:35.210
They want to determine a lot more
of the look and feel and how the

00:11:35.270 --> 00:11:38.510
project is presented and sort
of what face it puts forward.

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:43.680
So, that brings us to opendarwin.org,
which those of you who read Slashdot

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:45.520
have probably read about last week.

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:48.600
It basically was founded
jointly by Apple and the

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:51.100
Internet Software Consortium.

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:54.350
But Apple does not control the site.

00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:56.210
Apple has basically... Bootstrapped it.

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:59.740
It is now run day-to-day by the ISC,
however.

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:04.820
And the community will essentially
dictate how that project evolves.

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:05.980
Sorry again.

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:10.030
It's... The CVS repository
is completely open.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:13.810
So, you don't need to sign any
click-through licenses or do anything

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:15.660
special to check out sources.

00:12:15.660 --> 00:12:18.880
You can do it via non-CVS today.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:21.670
If you want to join the
project as a committer,

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:25.320
someone who has write access,
that's a fairly lightweight process.

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:26.670
You go to a little web page.

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:29.580
You fill out a form describing what
you want to do and who you are.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:32.890
And right now,
this is basically... It goes

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:35.940
to the opendarwin core team,
which has three people

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:38.840
to start with on it,
who will sort of eyeball it for

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:42.520
correctness and goodness and,
in pretty much all cases,

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:43.060
just to prove it.

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:47.210
All the bug tracking news
and documentation is now

00:12:47.210 --> 00:12:49.430
community maintained.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:53.350
So, we've adopted Bugzilla
for the time being.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:56.530
If people have a better solution,
we're certainly willing to hear it.

00:12:56.690 --> 00:12:58.670
Again, the community will drive this.

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:01.230
So, we will determine which
tools we want to use.

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:04.760
We will determine what sort of
infrastructure we want to provide.

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:07.860
And all of that is entirely
outside of Apple's control.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:14.350
We also would like to leverage
the infrastructure in interesting

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:15.790
new ways as we go along.

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:21.300
So, rather than just hosting Darwin and
OpenPlay and sort of projects like that,

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:23.750
we would like to look at new projects,
potentially.

00:13:23.870 --> 00:13:24.730
Some people have already come forward,
said, "Oh,

00:13:24.730 --> 00:13:27.020
we're going to do this." Some people have
already started saying they would like

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:30.840
to have kind of a working area to port
KDE to Darwin and be able to collaborate

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:34.060
and have their own CVS repository,
their own mailing lists.

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:38.140
And all of that infrastructure is
currently provided at opendarwin.org.

00:13:38.190 --> 00:13:40.130
So,
we can do that kind of thing very easily.

00:13:42.250 --> 00:13:44.940
So,
sort of a CVS map as it has existed up

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:47.980
to now and as it exists going forward.

00:13:47.980 --> 00:13:51.060
Right now, there's a one-way pool.

00:13:51.060 --> 00:13:54.460
You can, as a developer,
sign up for an account with

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:58.340
the Darwin project and have
read-only access to the bits,

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:00.360
basically the click-through license.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.290
If you make changes,
you can either get those changes

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:07.760
submitted via a web form,
or if you're a Darwin committer,

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:09.890
which is one of the select
few that can actually write,

00:14:09.950 --> 00:14:12.290
then...

00:14:12.570 --> 00:14:14.750
This can either go straight
back to the CVS repository

00:14:14.750 --> 00:14:18.270
if you're a Darwin committer,
or somebody at Apple looks at the

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:22.000
web form submissions and commits
it for you if they deem it worthy.

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:26.360
So now we have kind of an
interesting new piece of the puzzle.

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:31.520
OpenDarwin.org is a completely
separate CVS repository,

00:14:31.520 --> 00:14:32.120
as I said.

00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:35.520
And what we're basically
doing is we will pull,

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:39.930
on an hourly basis,
copies of the Darwin CVS repository onto

00:14:40.010 --> 00:14:43.520
OpenDarwin.org as a reference repository.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:45.570
That will not be the live repository.

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:48.390
That will simply be there close
at hand for the convenience of

00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:50.020
the committers in OpenDarwin.

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:52.700
We'll probably also,
we haven't done this yet,

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:55.340
but we'll probably mirror
the FreeBSD CVS repository,

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:58.910
NATBSD, OpenBSD,
any other reference code bases

00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:02.090
we think might be valuable or
interesting will be available for

00:15:02.110 --> 00:15:04.590
reference purposes on OpenDarwin.org.

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:07.340
However,
the live OpenDarwin CVS repository,

00:15:07.420 --> 00:15:11.450
which has started out sort of basically
being a copy of the Darwin CVS but

00:15:11.450 --> 00:15:15.020
can now migrate or mutate in all
kinds of interesting new ways,

00:15:15.020 --> 00:15:16.900
will be a two-way street.

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:20.450
So the community can commit
their changes straight to it.

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:21.370
They can pull it.

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:23.640
They can have a lot more
control over where it goes.

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:28.140
Some of the initiatives we've
been working on in Darwin as well

00:15:28.140 --> 00:15:33.250
are just overall make Darwin and
Mac OS X a better Unix citizen.

00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:36.740
Make it easier to port
legacy applications.

00:15:36.740 --> 00:15:41.080
We've heard a lot of requests for
some sort of ports collection.

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:45.020
And as one of the original authors
of the FreeBSD ports collection,

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:48.840
I obviously have a lot of ideas
on how that might be evolved.

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:51.700
And maybe it's second system syndrome.

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:54.210
Maybe it's really the
benefit of hindsight at work.

00:15:54.300 --> 00:15:54.800
I'm not sure.

00:15:55.220 --> 00:15:59.500
But my team is working on something
along the lines of the FreeBSD ports

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:01.800
collection for Darwin right now.

00:16:01.820 --> 00:16:05.540
We hope it will be a lot more
extensible and scalable in many ways.

00:16:05.540 --> 00:16:11.500
We're also looking constantly at
people's requests for more Unix APIs,

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:14.770
more standard POSIX calls that
might have been missing up to

00:16:14.770 --> 00:16:16.080
now for one reason or the other.

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:19.440
Missing headers, libraries,
basically anything people need to be

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:21.340
able to port software more easily.

00:16:21.340 --> 00:16:24.620
And one thing you're going to
see in the next development.

00:16:24.790 --> 00:16:28.100
Developers CD is something
called the BSD SDK,

00:16:28.110 --> 00:16:32.390
which includes all of the headers
and libraries for things that

00:16:32.450 --> 00:16:35.370
people have been missing up to now,
like OpenSSL, for example.

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:37.700
If you have a legacy
application that uses OpenSSL,

00:16:37.740 --> 00:16:39.280
you don't want to port it to CDSA.

00:16:39.340 --> 00:16:40.230
That's no problem.

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:41.000
We've got you covered.

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:44.950
We'll ship the full headers from
now on in the BSD SDK package.

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:49.020
Same goes for TCL, Libcurl, Libbzip,
a whole bunch of different things

00:16:49.130 --> 00:16:51.430
will basically go into that bucket.

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:54.580
So when you install the developer tools,
just click on the custom.

00:16:54.580 --> 00:16:54.580
Okay.

00:16:54.580 --> 00:16:54.670
Okay.

00:16:54.750 --> 00:16:57.880
And check it off on the list,
and you'll get all that

00:16:57.880 --> 00:16:59.320
stuff now for free.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:03.920
Again, this is for porting
legacy Unix applications.

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:07.010
Obviously, there are a lot of high-level
APIs that you can and should use

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:08.820
if you're writing new applications.

00:17:08.820 --> 00:17:11.740
But this is all designed
to make it easier for Unix

00:17:11.910 --> 00:17:13.560
folks to port their stuff.

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:18.760
We are, as I said, actively working on
synchronizing with FreeBSD.

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:22.200
We've done some major code
pull-ups from FreeBSD 4.4 recently.

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:24.480
And this is an ongoing process.

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:28.710
We hope to track FreeBSD with far
less latency than we have in the past.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:32.260
Darwin was originally
forked from FreeBSD 3.2.

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:35.190
So as you might expect,
there was a lot of work that we

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:38.130
needed to do to kind of bring it
up to snuff and bring it current.

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:41.120
But we have more bodies
on this problem now,

00:17:41.120 --> 00:17:44.930
and we hope to be staying much more
closely in sync with FreeBSD and

00:17:44.970 --> 00:17:46.520
other open source projects as well.

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:50.360
And last but definitely not least,
we are definitely working on

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:52.250
making Darwin easier to build.

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:54.580
And this is another goal.

00:17:54.580 --> 00:17:57.420
And this is a goal that OpenDarwin
Project will be instrumental on,

00:17:57.420 --> 00:18:00.540
because its developers won't be
able to be very effective until

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:04.140
they can build the entire system,
install it on another system,

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:06.270
and sort of have reproducible results.

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:09.760
So I hope that the community will
get actively involved in this and

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:11.810
helping us to evolve that process.

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:14.130
Oops.

00:18:14.770 --> 00:18:17.800
Some new things that are in Darwin,
as Brett has already said.

00:18:17.810 --> 00:18:21.860
We are fully supporting the
Linux slash BSD PAM API.

00:18:21.860 --> 00:18:24.100
So if you have PAM modules
from other Unix systems,

00:18:24.110 --> 00:18:25.900
they should port straight across.

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:28.180
We also have a PAM module
for security frameworks,

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:31.620
which means there's basically one
chain of authentication by default.

00:18:31.660 --> 00:18:34.250
It would be pretty confusing
if it was a Y shape,

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:36.480
so that's not the default behavior.

00:18:36.480 --> 00:18:39.200
But if you're an administrator and you
know what you're doing and you want

00:18:39.200 --> 00:18:41.660
to have different PAM authenticators,
you can plug them in,

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:43.520
you can change the ordering,
it's all up to you.

00:18:44.720 --> 00:18:46.800
We are now a first
class Kerberos citizen.

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:51.170
We have been working very closely with
MIT over the last year to provide a

00:18:51.170 --> 00:18:56.080
world class Kerberos implementation,
a full Kerberos implementation.

00:18:56.080 --> 00:18:59.440
And we have integrated that into
security frameworks as well,

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:03.640
so now everything from Telnet to the
login window can support Kerberos.

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:07.520
And we've updated many,
many different pieces.

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:11.460
As I say, there was the FreeBSD merge,
but we've also updated Apache, SendMail,

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:12.500
Emacs, Samba.

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:14.580
We brought Samba into the desktop.

00:19:14.750 --> 00:19:17.220
We've brought in the product by default,
so you can do SMB sharing

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:18.190
from the desktop.

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:20.630
We've brought in a bunch
of additional languages.

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:21.900
We've brought in Python.

00:19:21.950 --> 00:19:25.420
So we're listening very closely to
what the Unix community has been

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:27.030
asking for and updating those things.

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:31.080
And as I said, we're always working on
cleaning up the APIs.

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:36.100
We basically want to be a really good
Unix from a perspective of portability.

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:39.990
We've also been working pretty
closely with the X486 project.

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:42.620
Tory Lyons, who unfortunately couldn't
be here this year,

00:19:42.620 --> 00:19:46.920
is a Darwin committer and
a X486 core team member,

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:49.120
or at least a prominent developer.

00:19:49.120 --> 00:19:53.380
And he has done a lot of work,
along with the rest of the X486 team,

00:19:53.420 --> 00:19:57.220
in making sure that X486 is
well supported on Mac OS X.

00:19:57.220 --> 00:20:01.240
You can now run it on a separate display,
or you can run it rootless,

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:04.120
which means your X windows show
up on the same desktop as your

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:05.860
Mac OS X native applications.

00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:10.610
And the basic goals,
as I understand them,

00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:13.090
are to work on acceleration now.

00:20:13.140 --> 00:20:15.720
Phase one was to make it
work and make it work well,

00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:17.800
