00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:07.040
One year ago, we started looking for a
printing system for Darwin.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:10.160
The obvious answer was LPD,
but just as Darwin is the

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:13.910
substrate for Mac OS X,
we wanted a printing system in

00:22:13.910 --> 00:22:17.500
Darwin that would also be the
basis for our OS X printing system.

00:22:17.500 --> 00:22:19.370
And to be kind,
LPD just wasn't going to cut it.

00:22:21.210 --> 00:22:23.930
So we started looking,
we broadened our search a little bit,

00:22:23.930 --> 00:22:26.120
and we found CUPS,
Common Unix Printing System.

00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:31.910
It's written by a company in Maryland,
Easy Software Products.

00:22:34.460 --> 00:22:37.330
Cups is available under the
GNU General Public License,

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:39.620
so it's open source,
and so we can use it in Darwin.

00:22:39.620 --> 00:22:43.400
It's also built upon the
Internet Printing Protocol.

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:45.430
Luckily for us,
our Mac OS X printing system

00:22:45.460 --> 00:22:48.790
was also designed around the
Internet Printing Protocol,

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:50.390
so we had a nice fit there.

00:22:50.670 --> 00:22:55.790
Cups includes strong PostScript printer
description file format support.

00:22:55.920 --> 00:22:57.680
In fact, that's really the core of Cups.

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:02.060
We've been using PPDs on Mac OSes
going back about 10 or 12 years.

00:23:02.060 --> 00:23:04.010
So again, a very nice fit for us.

00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:08.740
Cups includes both BSD and System 5
command line tools for printing.

00:23:08.810 --> 00:23:10.830
This was very important to us.

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:13.240
We wanted people who were coming
to Darwin to feel very comfortable

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:14.460
when they started printing.

00:23:14.460 --> 00:23:16.330
So whichever flavor of
Unix you're coming from,

00:23:16.350 --> 00:23:18.580
you'll find the commands to
print that you're used to.

00:23:18.620 --> 00:23:20.640
Cups is well documented.

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:23.550
The Easy Software folks do an
excellent job of documenting Cups.

00:23:23.550 --> 00:23:26.960
There's a vibrant community
surrounding Cups as well.

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:29.860
That is also really anchored
by the Easy Software folks,

00:23:29.860 --> 00:23:33.790
but there are other parts of the open
source community that also back Cups.

00:23:33.900 --> 00:23:37.240
The KDE group is one great example,
as are some of the different

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:40.870
Linux distributions,
all backing Cups, all providing support,

00:23:40.870 --> 00:23:43.510
all providing momentum
as it moves forward.

00:23:45.580 --> 00:23:46.860
So how can you learn more about CUPS?

00:23:46.860 --> 00:23:48.820
Well, the obvious answer is to
go to the CUPS website.

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:52.260
And again,
Easy Software supports this website.

00:23:52.260 --> 00:23:55.100
You'll find mailing lists and
newsgroups on that website.

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:58.000
There are about a half dozen
documents there describing

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:02.350
CUPS from different vantage points,
be it user, administrator, or developer.

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:04.390
So you can go there.

00:24:04.540 --> 00:24:07.070
But the best way to learn
CUPS is to get the CUPS book.

00:24:07.180 --> 00:24:08.830
It's written by Michael Sweet.

00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:10.580
He is the architect of CUPS.

00:24:10.580 --> 00:24:11.940
It's an excellent book.

00:24:11.980 --> 00:24:13.040
I own three of them.

00:24:13.150 --> 00:24:14.910
I have them all over the place.

00:24:14.910 --> 00:24:18.120
And the Developer Depot folks
have been kind enough to stock

00:24:18.140 --> 00:24:20.120
them across the way for this week.

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:21.030
There's a limited number.

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:22.360
If you want one, I'd suggest you get one.

00:24:22.360 --> 00:24:23.890
But it really is the
best way to learn CUPS.

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:28.090
Once you've read the source code,
read the documentation, read the book,

00:24:28.090 --> 00:24:30.720
we'd love you to get
involved and help us out.

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:33.510
Again, this printing system is
not only part of Darwin,

00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:34.520
but also Mac OS X.

00:24:34.520 --> 00:24:36.760
So if you help us out with
the open source part of it,

00:24:36.760 --> 00:24:39.540
you'll see some of your changes
flowing through into Mac OS X.

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:41.550
We can never have enough printer drivers.

00:24:41.550 --> 00:24:43.620
So if you have a printer
that's not supported,

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:45.020
don't complain to me anymore.

00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:46.990
