00:26:53.300 --> 00:26:57.060
so what we are finally doing is
making that core technology that

00:26:57.060 --> 00:27:00.300
10.0 has been based on since day one
open source to the community so that

00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:02.870
it can be moved to other platforms,
and also just to show

00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:04.060
people how we do it.

00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:05.300
So it's part of Darwin.

00:27:05.300 --> 00:27:07.240
It's published on the website today.

00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:08.860
You can go and download the source bases.

00:27:08.860 --> 00:27:10.230
We'd love your feedback.

00:27:10.230 --> 00:27:12.410
My team is new to the
open source community,

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:15.160
so we're just starting to
monitor the Darwin thing,

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:18.180
and we got questions three years ago
as to when we would open source this,

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:20.040
and I can say, well, today's the day.

00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:22.980
So what is Open Directory?

00:27:23.060 --> 00:27:25.720
The first thing it entails
is Open Directory access.

00:27:25.720 --> 00:27:27.850
That consists of two major binaries.

00:27:27.980 --> 00:27:31.410
The Open Directory... Mac OS 10.0
directory service process and LookUpD,

00:27:31.510 --> 00:27:33.410
which has been part of
Darwin from day one.

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:36.030
It includes directory server technology.

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:38.980
We're integrating Open LDAP with
NetInfo for Jaguar,

00:27:38.980 --> 00:27:41.750
but we also have NetInfo,
and that has always been part

00:27:41.750 --> 00:27:44.510
of the open source technology,
so we have both an access

00:27:44.620 --> 00:27:46.480
technology and a server technology.

00:27:46.480 --> 00:27:51.200
Apple also ships a number of integrated
tools for managing the directory.

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:55.100
All of these tools, the desktop tools,
system preferences, users panel,

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:58.360
all of this Mac OS 10.0 server
tools use and are based on

00:27:58.480 --> 00:28:02.670
Open Directory technology,
so these tools can manage any data

00:28:02.670 --> 00:28:05.790
for which Open Directory can access.

00:28:05.840 --> 00:28:08.120
I think a picture might help you
understand directory services,

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:10.320
which is the standard
three-layer architecture.

00:28:10.340 --> 00:28:13.100
In the blue box,
you have Mac OS X software.

00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:17.580
If you call the directory service APIs,
it will figure out which directory

00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:21.520
system has been configured for access
and route it to the appropriate plug-in

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:23.080
that you see here in the red dialogs.

00:28:23.120 --> 00:28:26.780
What we've open sourced today is
NetInfo and the LDAPv2 plug-in.

00:28:26.780 --> 00:28:30.160
We will be open sourcing a
plug-in for BSD ETSI files,

00:28:30.200 --> 00:28:33.280
and there will be other plug-ins that
we'll be open sourcing in the future.

00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:35.890
If you want to hear about those plug-ins,
I encourage you to either

00:28:35.970 --> 00:28:37.840
speak with me afterwards or,
better yet,

00:28:37.840 --> 00:28:39.420
attend my session on Thursday.

00:28:39.420 --> 00:28:42.590
That's session 813,
and we'll be going into much more

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:43.940
detail about this architecture.

00:28:46.120 --> 00:28:49.100
So as part of Darwin today,
I'm sorry the URL is out of date.

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:53.950
www.apple.com.darwin will get
you to the Darwin website.

00:28:53.970 --> 00:28:57.370
Directory services consist of an
API framework and a daemon process.

00:28:57.530 --> 00:28:58.240
That's open source.

00:28:58.340 --> 00:29:02.520
LDAPv2, NetInfo, and we have a plugin
called the Search Policy,

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:06.150
which implements how the system
goes looking for users in a

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:08.380
multi-node directory system.

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:11.980
For Jaguar, we'll be open sourcing
DSAgent for LookUpD.

00:29:11.980 --> 00:29:15.360
We'll be open sourcing our
LDAPv3 ReadWrite plugin.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:19.270
And we'll be open sourcing our
BSD Configuration File plugin,

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:19.960
which is read-only.

00:29:19.960 --> 00:29:22.850
An opportunity for the community would
be to make that plugin read-write.

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:25.920
Service Discovery plugins
will be open sourced as well.

00:29:25.920 --> 00:29:31.700
And these plugins allow you to discover
services on the network via AppleTalk,

00:29:31.770 --> 00:29:35.820
Rendezvous, SLP,
and the SMB Windows protocol.

00:29:35.820 --> 00:29:38.160
So if you want to hear more about
the Service Discovery plugins,

00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:41.580
I would encourage you to
attend my session on Thursday.

00:29:44.840 --> 00:29:47.970
It's not only about directory access,
it's also about what Apple's providing

00:29:47.980 --> 00:29:49.820
as a directory server for our customers.

00:29:49.820 --> 00:29:53.260
For Mac OS 10.1,
NetInfo is included with Darwin and

00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:55.400
included with Mac OS 10.1.

00:29:55.440 --> 00:29:58.850
Mac OS, it's part of Darwin.

00:29:58.850 --> 00:30:02.500
It provides both a standalone and
shared network configuration repository,

00:30:02.500 --> 00:30:05.680
and many people have used this to manage
thousands of machines on their network.

00:30:05.770 --> 00:30:07.400
So NetInfo is open to the community.

00:30:07.470 --> 00:30:10.810
I believe it's already been ported
to Linux and some other platforms.

00:30:11.140 --> 00:30:16.090
We're adopting OpenLDAP for Jaguar,
so we have two open source,

00:30:16.220 --> 00:30:19.080
very powerful directory servers that
we're shipping as part of both TIN,

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:20.660
the retail product, and Darwin.

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:24.520
As a roadmap, there's the Darwin Birds of
the Feather session tonight.

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:27.430
I would encourage you to go to the
security and authorization session.

00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:31.550
Jordan mentioned earlier that our
PAM module calls the security framework.

00:30:31.620 --> 00:30:33.970
Well,
the security framework turns around and

00:30:34.010 --> 00:30:37.890
calls directory services in some cases
to verify the user's names and passwords.

00:30:37.960 --> 00:30:41.000
So that will give you more perspective.

00:30:41.140 --> 00:30:43.370
We're also working on how we're
tying PAM to the security framework

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:46.690
to directory services to allow
authentication to be out of any directory

00:30:46.690 --> 00:30:48.310
system of the customer's choice.

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:50.530
There's always the Darwin Feedback Forum.

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:53.430
There's my session on
Thursday for directory services,

00:30:53.570 --> 00:30:56.250
and following in the same exact
room is the Kerberos session.

00:30:56.280 --> 00:30:58.380
So I would encourage you
to attend that as well.

