00:31:04.280 --> 00:31:06.280
Thank you for your time.

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:10.920
Hi, everybody.

00:31:10.920 --> 00:31:14.860
So I'm going to talk pretty briefly
about Darwin Streaming Server.

00:31:14.860 --> 00:31:16.970
You're going to hear me say
QuickTime Streaming Server a lot,

00:31:17.110 --> 00:31:19.030
and the reason for that
is that Darwin Streaming

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:21.740
Server and QuickTime Streaming
Server are the same thing.

00:31:21.740 --> 00:31:25.150
Mac OS X, we call it QuickTime Streaming
Server or QTSS,

00:31:25.150 --> 00:31:26.780
so just be aware of that.

00:31:26.850 --> 00:31:28.860
So kind of a general status.

00:31:28.880 --> 00:31:31.420
We're about three years old now.

00:31:31.420 --> 00:31:33.700
We released the first version
of QuickTime Streaming

00:31:33.700 --> 00:31:36.180
Server in April of 99,
and we just released in

00:31:36.190 --> 00:31:39.120
February version 4 of the server,
and I'll go over some of the new

00:31:39.220 --> 00:31:40.280
features in a minute about that.

00:31:40.300 --> 00:31:43.460
Since then, we've had over 300,000
downloads of the server.

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:45.660
That's a lot of downloads for a server,
especially a streaming server,

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:48.110
which is a pretty narrow niche of people
who are doing streaming out there.

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:50.030
We obviously are open source.

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:53.120
That's why I'm here,
and we've made it so it's really

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:55.290
easy to port to other platforms.

00:31:55.300 --> 00:31:59.620
We have a couple of files that basically
provide whatever layer you need,

00:31:59.790 --> 00:32:04.000
that provide kind of a layer abstraction
or an abstraction from the OS,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:07.980
and it's really easy to port to
anything that's POSIX compliant.

00:32:08.120 --> 00:32:10.320
It's fairly, well,
kind of a medium effort to port it to

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:14.340
things that are not POSIX compliant,
and we're completely standards-based.

00:32:14.360 --> 00:32:19.220
Some of the other streaming solutions
out there use proprietary protocols

00:32:19.240 --> 00:32:21.600
and codecs and things like that.

00:32:21.600 --> 00:32:27.990
We are using RTSP, RTP, RTCP, SDP, HTTP,
MP3, and just about any other kind of

00:32:27.990 --> 00:32:33.170
streaming standard you can think
of or acronym you can think of.

00:32:33.180 --> 00:32:34.510
So what's new?

00:32:34.520 --> 00:32:39.960
In 4, we have... Enhanced the module API.

00:32:39.960 --> 00:32:45.960
So QuickTime streaming server contains a
module API sort of like what Apache has.

00:32:45.960 --> 00:32:49.710
You can write modules that can either
be dynamically loaded into the server

00:32:50.050 --> 00:32:52.960
or statically linked into the server if
you want to rebuild the server itself.

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:55.910
And this is basically where all the
functionality for the server comes from.

00:32:55.960 --> 00:33:00.960
So being able to stream
QuickTime movies was done as a module.

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:04.960
Being able to rebroadcast live
broadcast stuff was done as a module.

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:07.800
Being able to do access live
broadcast stuff was done as a module.

00:33:07.800 --> 00:33:09.800
And then the service logging
was done as a module.

00:33:09.800 --> 00:33:11.800
So everything's done as a module.

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:14.780
And we've enhanced the APIs as we
do in just about every release.

00:33:14.810 --> 00:33:18.800
I'll give you a little more detail
on what we did there in a minute.

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:21.640
We've completely
redesigned the web admin.

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:26.760
So QuickTime streaming server has
a web-based administration console.

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:28.700
Works in any browser.

00:33:28.870 --> 00:33:30.780
And we've basically just
completely revamped it.

00:33:30.840 --> 00:33:33.680
We hired a really good engineer
who's really good at this stuff.

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:34.800
And so it works a lot better.

00:33:34.800 --> 00:33:36.800
It looks a lot better.

00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:40.790
Much easier for developers to
extend if they want to extend it.

00:33:40.820 --> 00:33:43.880
And actually,
if you want to take a look at this stuff,

00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:47.440
you can come to our session later,
which I'll tell you about in a minute,

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:47.790
too.

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:50.800
We've added support for automated relays.

00:33:50.800 --> 00:33:54.780
So what that is is streaming
servers send streams to clients.

00:33:54.910 --> 00:33:57.070
Well, there are times when you may
need a streaming server to send

00:33:57.070 --> 00:34:00.790
a stream to another server,
which then sends off to a client.

00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:02.800
In the past,
that was pretty complicated to set up.

00:34:02.800 --> 00:34:05.800
So we've kind of made it
so it's automatic now.

00:34:05.950 --> 00:34:08.800
Server A can announce to Server B that
it wants to relay something,

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:12.800
and it just magically works
using standard protocols again.

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:14.800
And we've added UI for
that in the web admin.

00:34:16.270 --> 00:34:18.640
and we've added native MP3 streaming.

00:34:18.770 --> 00:34:22.860
And what I mean by native
MP3 streaming is shoutcast,

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:25.520
icecast compatible streaming.

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:27.100
We don't do encoding.

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:29.490
All we do is the
reflection of the stream,

00:34:29.670 --> 00:34:32.640
but we've, because we're using
standard protocols again,

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:36.270
you can use things like the LAME encoder
to hook into the stream if you

00:34:36.290 --> 00:34:38.620
want to do any kind of transcoding.

00:34:38.620 --> 00:34:42.250
We have support for serving
MP3 straight off disk though,

00:34:42.270 --> 00:34:44.480
but we're not doing any encoding.

00:34:46.430 --> 00:34:48.860
We've added MPEG-4 support.

00:34:49.210 --> 00:34:56.060
QuickTime Streaming Server can now
serve any ISO-compliant MPEG-4 file.

00:34:56.060 --> 00:35:03.540
That means that in addition to being able
to send streams to QuickTime players,

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:07.660
you can now send to any
compliant MPEG-4 player.

00:35:07.750 --> 00:35:11.240
We expect this to really open things up.

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:13.810
This is a great new standard.

00:35:14.550 --> 00:35:17.780
And as always,
we've made some performance improvements.

00:35:17.890 --> 00:35:20.880
So let me show you the performance
improvements we've done this time.

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:25.020
So back with QTSS 1,
we were doing 1,000 streams

00:35:25.090 --> 00:35:26.880
off a single machine.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:28.700
And with each release
we've increased that.

00:35:28.700 --> 00:35:31.330
We're now up to 4,000.

00:35:31.370 --> 00:35:33.840
And I think with the next release,
we'll probably be going

00:35:33.840 --> 00:35:35.120
a little bit higher even.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:38.760
I think we've got a few
more tricks up our sleeves.

00:35:38.840 --> 00:35:41.440
In terms of the module API enhancements,

00:35:42.820 --> 00:35:46.560
So you can build more powerful
and new types of modules now.

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:51.360
And the major reason for this is
our API is really object oriented.

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:55.350
And what I mean by that is that
there are actual objects that get

00:35:55.350 --> 00:35:59.110
passed into modules and they can
call methods on those objects.

00:35:59.200 --> 00:36:03.610
Prior to QTSS 4, though,
modules could not declare and

00:36:03.630 --> 00:36:06.950
instantiate their own objects,
objects that they owned.

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:08.270
And they can do that now.

00:36:08.270 --> 00:36:11.240
And that makes it easier to
write much more powerful modules.

00:36:12.400 --> 00:36:15.230
We've also listened to developers
and provided some documentation

00:36:15.320 --> 00:36:17.180
on some things that people
have been screaming for.

00:36:17.180 --> 00:36:19.700
We've documented our
reliable RTP protocol,

00:36:19.700 --> 00:36:22.820
which the marketing term is
skip protection for that.

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:26.300
So if anybody's writing a compliant
player or a compliant server,

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:27.760
that's documented now.

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:33.280
We've also documented our implementation
of tunneling RTSP over HTTP.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:35.320
So if you want to write a
server or a player again,

00:36:35.330 --> 00:36:36.360
that's documented.

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:40.250
And we've also got some
caching protocol extensions.

00:36:40.590 --> 00:36:45.430
So for developers who are writing
streaming caches or proxies,

00:36:45.480 --> 00:36:49.290
we've documented those extensions
so that they can take advantage of

00:36:49.310 --> 00:36:52.280
some of the really good things that
those protocol extensions provide.

00:36:55.070 --> 00:36:55.760
So here's where I beg.

00:36:55.760 --> 00:37:03.560
So if you want to help us out,
we have a lot of pressure to get

00:37:03.570 --> 00:37:07.130
new features into the release or
into the server every release.

00:37:07.140 --> 00:37:09.560
So some of the things that are
really difficult for my team to do

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:12.460
are some of the things that would be
nice for the open source community,

00:37:12.460 --> 00:37:13.740
like autoconf support.

00:37:13.740 --> 00:37:16.640
I would love it if somebody
would raise their hand right now.

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:17.280
Anybody?

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:19.120
And volunteer for autoconf support.

00:37:20.610 --> 00:37:23.420
Also, we have great packaging
mechanism on Mac OS X.

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:28.090
On the other platforms,
we basically live with

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:29.280
tar files and zip files.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:32.320
And it would be really nice if
somebody could kind of step up

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:35.210
and do some native packaging,
like install Shield for

00:37:35.210 --> 00:37:36.830
Windows or RPMs for Linux.

00:37:36.840 --> 00:37:39.980
And as always,
developer documentation is always

00:37:39.980 --> 00:37:42.120
something we could use help with.

00:37:42.280 --> 00:37:45.180
Just documenting how the
server works internally,

00:37:45.180 --> 00:37:48.080
documenting the source code,
things like that.

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:50.140
So that's my plea for help.

00:37:52.420 --> 00:37:55.380
Places that you can learn more
about this online are we have

00:37:55.380 --> 00:37:57.160
a mailing list for developers.

00:37:57.160 --> 00:38:00.300
It's pretty low traffic and
it's pretty high quality.

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:06.820
You can go to lists.apple.com and it's
a streaming server developers mailing

00:38:06.820 --> 00:38:06.820
list that you want to subscribe to.

00:38:07.050 --> 00:38:09.920
I can always go up to the Apple open
source website to find more

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:13.140
information about the Darwin Streaming
Server as well as any of the

00:38:13.180 --> 00:38:15.000
open source projects at Apple.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:19.070
And because the QuickTime Streaming
Server is the Darwin Streaming Server and

00:38:19.070 --> 00:38:22.520
we also work very tightly with QuickTime,
the QuickTime site is also a great place

00:38:22.520 --> 00:38:27.090
for getting information about some of
the things you can do with the server.

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:31.380
And in terms of a roadmap,
so we've got a full-blown streaming

00:38:31.530 --> 00:38:35.600
server session on Thursday,
and we'll have some engineers showing

00:38:35.600 --> 00:38:39.280
how you can customize the server,
how to write a module, things like that.

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:43.580
We'll go into the new features in a
little bit more detail as well there.

00:38:43.580 --> 00:38:45.770
There's a session on
QuickTime and MPEG-4.

00:38:45.870 --> 00:38:47.660
If you want to get a
technical overview of that,

00:38:47.660 --> 00:38:48.950
that's Friday in Room A2.

00:38:49.050 --> 00:38:52.160
And we will have server people
at the QuickTime feedback forum,

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:53.400
so if you want to provide
any feedback there,

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:54.460
we'd be happy.

00:38:54.460 --> 00:38:56.200
We'd love to hear it.

